│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe miscompile arises because a tautological        │
│ boolean expression (C or !C) that should fold to 'true' (and then inverted to │
│ 'false' for the return value) is incorrectly transformed into a value         │
│ depending on C. This changes the function result from a constant 0 to a value │
│ derived from the signed comparison. The initial simplification of the         │
│ load/store of the alloca (%flag) is correct; the semantic break occurs later  │
│ when InstCombine rewrites the compare (%cmp) and its negation through         │
│ aggressive predicate inversion inside foldNot/freelyInvertAllUsersOf.\n\n2.   │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nKey log excerpts:\n- %not1 = xor i1 %phi, true; %phi    │
│ replaced by %cmp -> not1 = xor cmp,true\n- foldNot triggers on pattern 'not   │
│ (cmp A, B)' and inverts predicate: icmp slt %x, -1 becomes icmp sge %x, -1\n- │
│ freelyInvertAllUsersOf(compare) then replaces the outer xor and adjusts       │
│ users, but in this case one user (%or) simultaneously uses both the original  │
│ compare and its negation. After the rewrite, %or degenerates from 'cmp or     │
│ !cmp' (always true) to 'cmp or cmp' (cmp), losing the tautology. Further      │
│ folding leads to final IR computing %cmp instead of the constant false.\nThe  │
│ critical transformation is: IC: Replacing %cmp.not = xor i1 %cmp, true with   │
│ %cmp = icmp sge i8 %x, -1. This shows the compare's predicate being inverted  │
│ while its SSA name (%cmp) is reused, effectively swapping meaning without     │
│ updating all dependent logical relationships correctly.\n\n3. Root Cause      │
│ Analysis:\nfoldNot (InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp) applies the predicate inversion  │
│ for the pattern 'xor %cmp, true' even when the compare has multiple uses and  │
│ is involved in a structure that also uses both %cmp and its negation together │
│ (e.g., 'or %cmp, (xor %cmp, true)'). The guard condition currently allows     │
│ inversion when either the compare has one use OR                              │
│ canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf(compare) returns true. canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf    │
│ only adapts direct users (branches, selects, xors) but cannot preserve        │
│ higher-level tautologies where a logic op combines a value and its negation.  │
│ In this test, after inverting the compare the expression (cmp OR (NOT cmp))   │
│ collapses incorrectly.\nThus the legality check is insufficient: the          │
│ transformation is not semantics-preserving for multi-use compares             │
│ participating in both sides of a tautology. We must restrict inversion to     │
│ single-use compares (or implement a much more complex structural safety       │
│ check). The simplest safe fix is to require NotOp->hasOneUse() for this       │
│ fold.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nFile:                                    │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp\nLines ~4688-4699     │
│ (the 'not (cmp...)' handling inside foldNot).\nChange the                     │
│ condition:\nCurrent:\nif (match(NotOp, m_Cmp(Pred, m_Value(), m_Value()))     │
│ &&\n    (NotOp->hasOneUse() ||\n                                              │
│ InstCombiner::canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf(cast<Instruction>(NotOp),             │
│ /*IgnoredUser=*/nullptr))) {\n  ...\n}\nProposed:\nif (match(NotOp,           │
│ m_Cmp(Pred, m_Value(), m_Value())) && NotOp->hasOneUse()) {\n  // Only invert │
│ predicate when the compare has a single use (the xor). Multi-use\n  // cases  │
│ can participate in tautologies (e.g., C or !C) that would be broken by\n  //  │
│ predicate inversion combined with user adaptation.\n                          │
│ cast<CmpInst>(NotOp)->setPredicate(CmpInst::getInversePredicate(Pred));\n     │
│ freelyInvertAllUsersOf(NotOp);\n  return &I;\n}\nRemove the alternative path  │
│ using canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf() for multi-use compares.\nRationale:         │
│ Prevents unsound inversion where both value and its negation are consumed     │
│ together. This matches conservative correctness and still handles the common  │
│ single-use pattern.\n\n(If exact line numbers shift slightly, ensure the edit │
│ encompasses the 'not (cmp A,B)' if block inside foldNot.)\n\n5.               │
│ Conclusion:\nBy tightening the guard to require single-use compares for       │
│ predicate inversion in foldNot, we avoid miscompiling expressions that rely   │
│ on the coexistence of a compare and its negation (e.g., C or !C). This        │
│ preserves tautological reductions to constants and prevents the incorrect     │
│ replacement seen in the reproducer. Expected effect: The test will now retain │
│ the tautology and ultimately fold to the correct constant return value (0),   │
│ eliminating the semantic mismatch.\n"})                                       │
