│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The miscompile arises because a tautological boolean expression (C or !C)     │
│ that should fold to 'true' (and then inverted to 'false' for the return       │
│ value) is incorrectly transformed into a value depending on C. This changes   │
│ the function result from a constant 0 to a value derived from the signed      │
│ comparison. The initial simplification of the load/store of the alloca        │
│ (%flag) is correct; the semantic break occurs later when InstCombine rewrites │
│ the compare (%cmp) and its negation through aggressive predicate inversion    │
│ inside foldNot/freelyInvertAllUsersOf.                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ Key log excerpts:                                                             │
│ - %not1 = xor i1 %phi, true; %phi replaced by %cmp -> not1 = xor cmp,true     │
│ - foldNot triggers on pattern 'not (cmp A, B)' and inverts predicate: icmp    │
│ slt %x, -1 becomes icmp sge %x, -1                                            │
│ - freelyInvertAllUsersOf(compare) then replaces the outer xor and adjusts     │
│ users, but in this case one user (%or) simultaneously uses both the original  │
│ compare and its negation. After the rewrite, %or degenerates from 'cmp or     │
│ !cmp' (always true) to 'cmp or cmp' (cmp), losing the tautology. Further      │
│ folding leads to final IR computing %cmp instead of the constant false.       │
│ The critical transformation is: IC: Replacing %cmp.not = xor i1 %cmp, true    │
│ with %cmp = icmp sge i8 %x, -1. This shows the compare's predicate being      │
│ inverted while its SSA name (%cmp) is reused, effectively swapping meaning    │
│ without updating all dependent logical relationships correctly.               │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ foldNot (InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp) applies the predicate inversion for the     │
│ pattern 'xor %cmp, true' even when the compare has multiple uses and is       │
│ involved in a structure that also uses both %cmp and its negation together    │
│ (e.g., 'or %cmp, (xor %cmp, true)'). The guard condition currently allows     │
│ inversion when either the compare has one use OR                              │
│ canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf(compare) returns true. canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf    │
│ only adapts direct users (branches, selects, xors) but cannot preserve        │
│ higher-level tautologies where a logic op combines a value and its negation.  │
│ In this test, after inverting the compare the expression (cmp OR (NOT cmp))   │
│ collapses incorrectly.                                                        │
│ Thus the legality check is insufficient: the transformation is not            │
│ semantics-preserving for multi-use compares participating in both sides of a  │
│ tautology. We must restrict inversion to single-use compares (or implement a  │
│ much more complex structural safety check). The simplest safe fix is to       │
│ require NotOp->hasOneUse() for this fold.                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp                 │
│ Lines ~4688-4699 (the 'not (cmp...)' handling inside foldNot).                │
│ Change the condition:                                                         │
│ Current:                                                                      │
│ if (match(NotOp, m_Cmp(Pred, m_Value(), m_Value())) &&                        │
│     (NotOp->hasOneUse() ||                                                    │
│      InstCombiner::canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf(cast<Instruction>(NotOp),        │
│ /*IgnoredUser=*/nullptr))) {                                                  │
│   ...                                                                         │
│ }                                                                             │
│ Proposed:                                                                     │
│ if (match(NotOp, m_Cmp(Pred, m_Value(), m_Value())) && NotOp->hasOneUse()) {  │
│   // Only invert predicate when the compare has a single use (the xor).       │
│ Multi-use                                                                     │
│   // cases can participate in tautologies (e.g., C or !C) that would be       │
│ broken by                                                                     │
│   // predicate inversion combined with user adaptation.                       │
│   cast<CmpInst>(NotOp)->setPredicate(CmpInst::getInversePredicate(Pred));     │
│   freelyInvertAllUsersOf(NotOp);                                              │
│   return &I;                                                                  │
│ }                                                                             │
│ Remove the alternative path using canFreelyInvertAllUsersOf() for multi-use   │
│ compares.                                                                     │
│ Rationale: Prevents unsound inversion where both value and its negation are   │
│ consumed together. This matches conservative correctness and still handles    │
│ the common single-use pattern.                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ (If exact line numbers shift slightly, ensure the edit encompasses the 'not   │
│ (cmp A,B)' if block inside foldNot.)                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By tightening the guard to require single-use compares for predicate          │
│ inversion in foldNot, we avoid miscompiling expressions that rely on the      │
│ coexistence of a compare and its negation (e.g., C or !C). This preserves     │
│ tautological reductions to constants and prevents the incorrect replacement   │
│ seen in the reproducer. Expected effect: The test will now retain the         │
│ tautology and ultimately fold to the correct constant return value (0),       │
│ eliminating the semantic mismatch.                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
